    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i was reading about muscle growth and saw two different terms: mechanical tension and metabolic stress. can you explain the difference between them and which one is actually more important for hypertrophy?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Mechanical tension and metabolic stress are two primary drivers of muscle growth (hypertrophy). Mechanical tension refers to the physical tension placed on the muscle fibers during resistance training, which is a direct signal for growth. Metabolic stress involves the accumulation of metabolites like lactate within the muscle during intense workouts. While both contribute, most current research suggests that high mechanical tension is the more critical and primary stimulus for significant muscle hypertrophy.",
      "source": "target",
